 origins, with dated language and at times uncritical analysis, it advocates for Indigenous legal, political and religious rights and offers important insights into how psychedelic researchers, who were themselves embattled in debates over the value of spirituality in medicine, interpreted the peyote ceremony. Ultimately, they championed peyotism as a spiritual practice that they believed held distinct cultural benefits. “A Culture’s Catalyst” revives a historical debate. Revisiting it now encourages us to reconsider how peyote has been understood and how its appearance in the 1950s tested Native-newcomer relations and the Canadian government’s attitudes toward Indigenous religious and cultural practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMedicinexCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMedicinezCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxReligionxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxRites and ceremoniesxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxReligion. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxRites and ceremonies. 0aIndiansxMedicinezCanada. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexMédecinexCanada. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexRelations avec l'ÉtatxCanadaxCanada. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexReligionxCanada. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexRites et cérémoniesxCanada. 0aPeyotismxCanada. 0aPeyotismzCanada. 0aPeyotlxCultexCanada. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aBlewett, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyck, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffer, Abram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahan, Fannie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsmond